INSERT INTO "Book" (id, subject, grade, "imgUrl")
INSERT INTO "Unit" (id, title, "BookId") VALUES ('u1', 'Unit 1: Biotechnology', 'b1');
INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, title, "unitId", index) VALUES ('l1', 'Biotechnology', 'u1', 1);
INSERT INTO "RealParagraph" (id, content, "LessonId", "order") VALUES
('rp_u1_1', 'Biology, as you discovered last year, is the study of living organisms. Now, at the beginning of your grade 10 biology course, you are going to be studying biotechnology.', 'l1', 1),
('rp_u1_2', 'Biotechnology is the use of micro-organisms to make things that people want, often involving industrial production.', 'l1', 2),
('rp_u1_3', 'Biotechnology has always been extremely important. It involves ways of making and preserving foods and making alcoholic drinks. Traditional applications of biotechnology involve brewing beers, making wines, making bread, and making cheese and yoghurt. Modern applications of biotechnology include using genetic engineering to change crops and animals; producing new medicines; and helping to provide new energy sources.', 'l1', 3),
('rp_u1_4', 'Biotechnology is based on microbiology. As you know, microbiology is the study of micro-organisms – tiny living organisms including bacteria, viruses, fungi and protoctista, which are usually too small to be seen with the naked eye. Some micro-organisms cause disease; others are enormously useful to people – for example, they play a vital role in decay and the recycling of nutrients in the environment.', 'l1', 4),
('rp_u1_5', 'Not all types of micro-organism are used in biotechnology. The main groups are bacteria and fungi, although viruses are being used more and more for genetic engineering. Bacteria are single-celled organisms that are much smaller than the smallest plant and animal cells. Viruses are even smaller than bacteria. Moulds and yeasts are both fungi – living organisms which obtain their food from other dead or living organisms. Yeasts are single-celled organisms, while moulds are made up of thin, thread-like structures called hyphae.', 'l1', 5),
('rp_u1_6', 'Developing new applications of biotechnology is one of the fastest-growing industries around the world, and is beginning to grow in Ethiopia too. It is easy to think that biotechnology is very new, but much of it has been in use for thousands of years. Bacteria are used in the manufacture of irgo (yoghurt) and Ayib (cheese). Yeast is used to make many traditional Ethiopian fermented foods, including injera, and also to produce alcoholic drinks, such as tej and tella.', 'l1', 6),
('rp_u1_7', 'One of the most useful micro-organisms is yeast. The yeasts are single-celled organisms. Each yeast cell has a nucleus, cytoplasm and a membrane surrounded by a cell wall. The main way in which yeasts reproduce is by asexual budding – splitting into two, to form new yeast cells.', 'l1', 7),
('rp_u1_8', 'When yeasts have plenty of oxygen, they respire aerobically, breaking down sugar to provide energy for the cells, and producing water and carbon dioxide as waste products. But yeasts are useful because they can also respire anaerobically. When yeast cells break down sugar in the absence of oxygen, they produce ethanol (commonly referred to as alcohol) and carbon dioxide.', 'l1', 8),
('rp_u1_9', 'Aerobic respiration provides more energy than anaerobic respiration, allowing yeast cells to grow and reproduce. However, once they exist in large numbers, yeast cells can survive for a long time in low-oxygen conditions, and will break down all the available sugar to produce ethanol. The anaerobic respiration of yeast is sometimes referred to as fermentation.', 'l1', 9),
('rp_u1_10', 'When you make injera, grind your teff or barley and then add water. Mix it well and leave the dough at room temperature for about two days. Natural yeasts start to grow and respire in the dough. At first the yeast respires aerobically, although this may change to anaerobic respiration. The yeast produces carbon dioxide, making the mix rise a little and giving it a tangy flavour.', 'l1', 10),
('rp_u1_11', 'When fruits fall to the ground and begin to decay, wild yeasts on their skin break down the fruit sugar to form ethanol and carbon dioxide. We now use this same reaction in a controlled way to make drinks such as beer, tej and wine. In both cases the yeast has to be supplied with carbohydrates to act as an energy source for respiration.', 'l1', 11),
('rp_u1_12', 'Tej is one of the oldest drinks known to the human race – it has been known since at least 400 BC. When you make tej, you need honey, water and gesho leaf or gesho stick. Gesho gives a bitter edge to the brew, and wild yeasts found on the plant start the fermentation going. As the yeast colonies grow they start to respire anaerobically, and this produces ethanol and carbon dioxide.', 'l1', 12),
('rp_u1_13', 'In contrast, winemaking uses natural sugar, found in fruit such as grapes, as the energy source for the yeast. You press the fruit and mix the juice with yeast and water. You then let the yeast respire anaerobically until most of the sugar has been used up.', 'l1', 13),
('rp_u1_14', 'People began to domesticate animals quite early in human history. They soon realised that the milk female animals made for their babies could be used as food for us too. It didn’t take people long to discover ways of changing milk, turning it into milk-based foods with a much longer life than the original milk. These changes depend on the action of micro-organisms.', 'l1', 14),
('rp_u1_15', 'Traditionally, yoghurt is fermented whole milk. Yoghurt is formed by the action of bacteria on the lactose (milk sugar) in the milk. As the bacteria break down the lactose in the milk, they produce lactic acid, which gives the yoghurt its sharp, tangy taste. This is known as lactic fermentation.', 'l1', 15),
('rp_u1_16', 'Like yoghurt making, cheese making depends on the reactions of bacteria with milk changing the texture and taste, and also preserving the milk. The bacteria in cheese making also convert lactose to lactic acid, but they make much more lactic acid. As a result, the solid part (curds) is much more solid than in yoghurt.', 'l1', 16),
('rp_u1_17', 'Around the world traditional biotechnologies – brewing, winemaking, bread making and the production of yoghurt and cheese – are extremely important. In many countries they are not only carried out in the home on a small scale, they also take place in massive industrial production processes.', 'l1', 17),
('rp_u1_18', 'Genetic engineering involves changing the genetic material of an organism. Genetic material carries the instructions for a new organism, found in the nucleus of every cell. You take a small piece of information – a gene – from one organism and transfer it to the genetic material of a completely different organism.', 'l1', 18),
('rp_u1_19', 'A lot of new biotechnology relies on growing large numbers of micro-organisms on an industrial scale in large vessels, known as fermenters. Industrial fermenters usually have an oxygen supply, a stirrer, a water-cooled jacket to remove excess heat, and measuring instruments for continuous monitoring.', 'l1', 19),
('rp_u1_20', 'For many years, we have used selective breeding to change our livestock and crops. By using genetic engineering, we can introduce new characteristics very rapidly. Genetic engineering has been used to make crop plants that are resistant to drought and to disease, and to produce plants that make their own pesticide chemicals.', 'l1', 20),
('rp_u1_21', 'The new biotechnology is often used in food processing. Enzymes are produced by genetically engineered bacteria, and the enzymes are then used in the production of processed foods and drinks. It has even been used to create a completely new food based on fungi known as mycoprotein.', 'l1', 21),
('rp_u1_22', 'Biotechnology is extremely important in modern medicine. It is used to develop vaccines and to create new medicines. The first medicine that really relied on microbiology was penicillin. When genetically engineered bacteria are cultured on a large scale, they can make huge quantities of protein to make a number of drugs and hormones used as medicines, such as human insulin.', 'l1', 22),
('rp_u1_23', 'Everyone needs fuel of some sort to provide them with energy. The generation of biogas from human and animal waste is becoming increasingly important in both the developing and the developed world. Biogas is a flammable mixture of gases, formed when bacteria break down plant material, or the waste products of animals, in anaerobic conditions. It is mainly methane.', 'l1', 23),
('rp_u1_24', 'To produce biogas, you collect dung or plant material, which contains a high level of carbohydrates, and put it into a biogas generator or digester. Then you add a mixed population of many different types of bacteria which are needed to digest the carbohydrate. The biogas produced is passed along a pipe into your home, where you burn it to produce heat, light or refrigeration.', 'l1', 24),
('rp_u1_25', 'In countries such as Ethiopia, plants grow quickly. If sugar-rich products from cane and maize are fermented anaerobically with yeast, the sugars are broken down incompletely to give ethanol and water. You can extract the ethanol from the products of fermentation by distillation, and you can then use it in cars and other vehicles as a fuel.', 'l1', 25),
('rp_u1_26', 'In many ways, ethanol is an ideal fuel. It is efficient, and it does not produce toxic gases when you burn it. Using ethanol as a fuel is a carbon-neutral activity. This means there is no overall increase in carbon dioxide in the atmosphere when you burn ethanol. The original plants removed carbon dioxide from the air during photosynthesis.', 'l1', 26);
INSERT INTO "Unit" (id, title, "BookId") VALUES ('u2', 'Unit 2: Heredity', 'b1');
INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, title, "unitId", index) VALUES ('l2', 'Mitosis and Meiosis', 'u2', 2);
INSERT INTO "RealParagraph" (id, content, "LessonId", "order") VALUES
('rp_u2_1', 'Almost all the cells of your body – with the exception of your mature red blood cells – contain a nucleus, the ‘control room’ of the cell. Inside the nucleus of every cell there are thread-like structures called chromosomes. This is where the genetic information passed on from parent to child is stored.', 'l2', 1),
('rp_u2_2', 'The chromosomes are made up of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid). This amazing chemical carries the instructions needed to make all the proteins in your cells. Chromosomes come in pairs known as homologous pairs. Human karyotypes show 23 pairs of chromosomes. 22 of the pairs are known as the autosomes. The remaining pair of chromosomes are known as the sex chromosomes because they determine whether you are male or female.', 'l2', 2),
('rp_u2_3', 'DNA is a long molecule, made up of two strands twisted together to make a spiral known as a double helix. A nucleotide consists of a phosphate group, a sugar and a base. In DNA there are four different bases that appear time after time in different orders, but always paired up in the same way.', 'l2', 3),
('rp_u2_4', 'We now know that the bases that make up DNA are called adenine, thymine, guanine and cytosine. The two DNA strands are linked by these bases, where adenine pairs with thymine and cytosine pairs with guanine.', 'l2', 4),
('rp_u2_5', 'The order of the bases in the DNA acts as a code to instruct the cell about the order in which to join up the amino acids to make a particular protein. This is how the genes control what goes on in the cells and in the whole organism.', 'l2', 5),
('rp_u2_6', 'New cells are needed for an organism, or part of an organism, to grow. They are also needed to replace cells that become worn out and repair damaged tissue. Body cells (also known as somatic cells) divide to make new cells. The cell division that takes place in the normal body cells and produces identical cells is known as mitosis.', 'l2', 6),
('rp_u2_7', 'Before a cell divides, it produces new copies of the homologous pairs of chromosomes in the nucleus. Each chromosome forms two identical chromatids. Then the chromatids divide into two identical packages, and the rest of the cytoplasm divides as well to form two genetically identical daughter cells.', 'l2', 7),
('rp_u2_8', 'The cells in your body divide on a regular basis to bring about growth. They divide in a set sequence, known as the cell cycle, which involves several different stages: A period of active cell division, and a long period of non-division when the cells get bigger and replicate their DNA.', 'l2', 8),
('rp_u2_9', 'The reproductive organs in humans, as in most animals, are the ovaries and the testes. This is where the sex cells (the gametes) are made. The cell division that takes place in the reproductive organ cells and produces gametes is known as meiosis. Meiosis is a special form of cell division where the chromosome number is reduced by half.', 'l2', 9),
('rp_u2_10', 'For centuries people thought that the characteristics of the parents blended together so that the distinct characteristics of each parent were lost. Mendel developed a theory to explain his observations, based on independent particles of hereditary material, some of which were dominant over others but never mixed together.', 'l2', 10),
('rp_u2_11', 'The chromosomes we inherit carry our genetic information in the form of genes. Many of these genes have different forms, known as alleles. An allele is the particular form of information in that position on an individual chromosome.', 'l2', 11),
('rp_u2_12', 'Some alleles control the development of a characteristic even when they are only present on one of your chromosomes. These alleles are dominant. Some alleles control the development of a characteristic only if they are present on both chromosomes. These alleles are recessive.', 'l2', 12),
('rp_u2_13', 'If you inherit two identical alleles – whether they are dominant or recessive – you are homozygous for that trait. If you inherit one of each type of allele, you are heterozygous for the trait.', 'l2', 13),
('rp_u2_14', 'Mendel started all his crosses using homozygotes because they are true breeding. This means that if you cross two individuals who are homozygous for the same characteristic, all of the offspring of all the generations that follow will have the same characteristic.', 'l2', 14),
('rp_u2_15', 'A genetic diagram shows you the alleles for a characteristic carried by the parents, the possible gametes that can be formed from these and how they could combine to form the characteristic in their offspring.', 'l2', 15),
('rp_u2_16', 'To find out the genotype of an individual showing the effect of a dominant allele it must be crossed with a homozygous recessive individual. Because the recessive genes have no effect on the phenotype of the offspring unless they are in the homozygous state, this type of cross can reveal the required parental genotype. It is known as a test cross.', 'l2', 16),
('rp_u2_17', 'In most of the examples of monohybrid inheritance that you will be looking at, there is simple dominance of one allele over another. But it is important to realise that this isn’t always the case. Not all genes show dominance so aspects of both characteristics show through. This is common in the colour of the coat of certain cattle.', 'l2', 17),
('rp_u2_18', 'Your genetic inheritance from your parents often contains nothing worse than a big nose or a tendency to gain weight easily. However, sometimes the genetic combination you receive has more noticeable and dramatic effects. In the inherited condition known as albinism the melanin pigment in the skin, hair and eyes does not develop.', 'l2', 18),
('rp_u2_19', 'One area where understanding genetics is very important indeed is in the breeding of farm animals and crop plants. People manipulated the genetics of domestic animals and plants long before anyone understood how genetics works!', 'l2', 19),
('rp_u2_20', 'One way to improve the performance of a crop plant or domestic animal is to select the best possible individuals of that type and use them to build up your stock. Selective breeding is used to breed for particular traits.', 'l2', 20),
('rp_u2_21', 'An alternative way of improving a breed of animals or plants is to combine good traits from two different breeds. By selecting the offspring carefully and breeding again and again, eventually a new, true breeding type of goat or cow would emerge.', 'l2', 21),
('rp_u2_22', 'Ethiopia is a very big country. Many people rely on their crops and livestock for food, for milk, for hides and for their personal wealth. We have an enormous amount of genetic diversity in our farm animals and plants, which is important not just to Ethiopia but to the whole world as a source of new genetic material.', 'l2', 22);
INSERT INTO "Unit" (id, title, "BookId") VALUES ('u3', 'Unit 3: Human Biology', 'b1');
INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, title, "unitId", index) VALUES ('l3', 'The Nervous System and Senses', 'u3', 3);
INSERT INTO "RealParagraph" (id, content, "LessonId", "order") VALUES
('rp_u3_1', 'All living organisms need some level of awareness of their surroundings so they can avoid danger, find food and, in some cases, find a mate. Your body has two very different ways of bringing about this co-ordination and control: The nervous system and the endocrine (hormonal) system.', 'l3', 1),
('rp_u3_2', 'The nervous system has two main parts. The central nervous system (CNS) is made up of your brain and spinal cord. The peripheral (body) system is made up of the neurons (nerve cells) and the sensory receptors.', 'l3', 2),
('rp_u3_3', 'Once a stimulus is picked up by a sensory receptor, the information is passed along special nerve cells, affector or afferent neurons, to the central nervous system. Once the information has been processed in the CNS, instructions are sent out to the body along more neurons called effector or efferent neurons. These stimulate the effector organ, usually muscles or a gland.', 'l3', 3),
('rp_u3_4', 'The most distinctive feature of all nerve cells is the axon or nerve fibre, which is extremely long and thin. The nerve impulse travels along the axon from one place to another. Each nerve impulse is a minute electrical event that is the result of charge differences across the membrane of the axon. The wave of positive charge inside the axon when the neuron is stimulated is known as the action potential.', 'l3', 4),
('rp_u3_5', 'Whenever one neuron ends and another begins there is a gap known as a synapse. So when an impulse arrives at the end of a neuron, chemicals are released. These chemical transmitters (neurotransmitters) cross the synapse and are picked up by special receptor cells in the end of the next neuron. In turn this starts up an electrical impulse.', 'l3', 5),
('rp_u3_6', 'Your brain is a delicate mass of nervous tissue with the consistency of thick yoghurt. It is enclosed in membranes and protected by the bones of your skull in a space known as the cranium. The spinal cord runs out from your brain down your body. It is encased and protected by the vertebrae making up your spine.', 'l3', 6),
('rp_u3_7', 'The bulk of your brain is made up of grey matter – the cell bodies of neurons and the synapses that connect them. Inside the brain is the white matter – the axons that lead into and out of the brain.', 'l3', 7),
('rp_u3_8', 'Mental illness is a very general term that is difficult to define. It is the term we use to describe a wide variety of disorders and diseases, which are diagnosed as mental illnesses because they involve thought processes, emotional disturbances and/or behaviour that are considered abnormal.', 'l3', 8),
('rp_u3_9', 'Some of our responses to stimuli are purely automatic. When we touch something very hot we withdraw our hand before we are consciously aware of the sensation of pain. Reactions such as these are known as reflexes. Reflexes occur very fast. They are usually involved in helping us to avoid danger or damage.', 'l3', 9),
('rp_u3_10', 'The key point about a reflex action is that the messages do not reach a conscious area of your brain before instructions are sent out to take action. Many reflexes involve the spinal cord while others involve the brain. They involve three types of neuron – affector neurons, relay neurons and effector neurons. The receptors, neurons and effectors involved are referred to as a reflex arc.', 'l3', 10),
('rp_u3_11', 'Not all reflexes are simple. Some of them can be learnt. In 1902, a Russian scientist called Ivan Pavlov investigated conditioned reflex action using a dog. Since this reflex action was not innate (there at birth), it is a result of experience or learning. This learned reflex action is called a conditioned reflex action.', 'l3', 11),
('rp_u3_12', 'A drug is a substance which alters the way in which your mind, or body, or both, works. Drug (or substance) abuse is when you use a substance to the point of excess and/or dependence. Drug dependence is when you use a drug again and again and become addicted. When an addict tries to stop using their drug they will feel very unwell, experiencing withdrawal symptoms.', 'l3', 12),
('rp_u3_13', 'School surveys have shown that alcohol, khat, tobacco, cannabis (marijuana) and solvents are the substances most widely used in Ethiopia. Alcohol, khat and tobacco are legal drugs in Ethiopia, but cannabis is illegal.', 'l3', 13),
('rp_u3_14', 'The addictive drug in cigarette smoke is nicotine, which affects the brain and produces a sensation of calm well-being. Smoking increases your risk of Coronary Heart Disease, Strokes, Lung Disease, and Cancers.', 'l3', 14),
('rp_u3_15', 'Alcohol is poisonous. However, your liver can usually break it down. Alcohol is a diuretic, which means that it makes you lose water through increased urination. If you drink large amounts of alcohol, your liver simply cannot cope. You suffer from alcohol poisoning.', 'l3', 15),
('rp_u3_16', 'Khat is the leaves of the khat shrub. People chew fresh khat leaves which contain a drug which affects the brain. It is a mild stimulant, makes people feel happy and also reduces your appetite. The drug cathinone from the khat leaves is absorbed into the bloodstream through the membranes lining the mouth and the stomach.', 'l3', 16),
('rp_u3_17', 'Cannabis is a plant that contains 400 known chemicals, 60 of which, called the cannabinoids, are unique to the plant. The most potent is delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinoid (THC). It is a mild hallucinogenic drug. Hallucinogens are drugs that produce vivid waking dreams.', 'l3', 17),
('rp_u3_18', 'The excessive and wrong use of drugs is considered drug abuse. Drug use is sometimes accompanied by aggressive and abusive behaviour. Using drugs reduces your ability to concentrate, to pay attention and to think logically and clearly. Drug users often become suspicious of others, which can lead them into arguments and fights.', 'l3', 18),
('rp_u3_19', 'A sensory organ is an organ that contains a large number of sensory receptor cells and the human eye is a good example. Our eyes enable us to see in clear focus, in three dimensions and in colour.', 'l3', 19),
('rp_u3_20', 'The white outer layer of the eye, the sclera, is very tough and strong so the eyeball is not easy to damage. It has a transparent area at the front known as the cornea, which lets light into the eye. The rest of the sclera has many blood vessels, which supply your retina with food and oxygen, and a dark layer underneath – the choroid.', 'l3', 20),
('rp_u3_21', 'The iris is the coloured part of the eye. It is made up of muscles that contract or relax to control the size of the pupil and so to control the amount of light reaching the retina. Once light has entered your inner eye through the pupil it passes through the lens, a clear disc made up largely of proteins. The lens is held in place by suspensory ligaments and the ciliary muscles.', 'l3', 21),
('rp_u3_22', 'All of the light-sensitive cells are arranged together in a special light-sensitive layer at the back of the eye known as the retina. The light-sensitive cells known as the rods and cones contain chemicals that change when light falls on them. Rods respond to relatively low light levels, but they do not give a very clear image and they do not respond to different colours. Cones only work properly in bright light – but they respond to colours and give very clear, defined images.', 'l3', 22),
('rp_u3_23', 'Ability of the human eye to focus on objects at different distances is known as accommodation. A short-sighted person can focus clearly on things that are close to them but has much more difficulty with objects in the distance. A long-sighted person can focus clearly on things that are at a distance but has much more difficulty with objects close to them.', 'l3', 23),
('rp_u3_24', 'Your ears are specialised organs which enable you to hear sound. They are also concerned with the balance and position of the body. The ear is divided into three regions: the outer ear, middle ear and inner ear. The pinna helps to trap and funnel sound into the ear. At the end of the ear canal is a sheet of very thin membrane called the eardrum or tympanum.', 'l3', 24),
('rp_u3_25', 'Behind the eardrum is a cavity filled with air. This cavity contains three tiny bones called the malleus (hammer), the incus (anvil) and the stapes (stirrup). The cavity of the middle ear is connected to your throat by a tube called the Eustachian tube.', 'l3', 25),
('rp_u3_26', 'The inner ear consists of a cavity filled with a fluid, two sac-like structures called the sacculus and utriculus, three semicircular canals and a coiled tube called the cochlea. When sound waves hit the eardrum, it vibrates. These vibrations are transmitted through the ear ossicles to the oval window. Vibrations of the fluid cause the hair-like sensory cells to move, producing nerve impulses.', 'l3', 26),
('rp_u3_27', 'The semicircular canals in your inner ear are concerned with the detection of motion. Whenever the body or the head moves, the fluid in the semicircular canals causes the cupula to tilt, pressing the hairs of the sensory cells. The brain interprets the direction and speed of motion.', 'l3', 27),
('rp_u3_28', 'The sensory receptors of your tongue and those found in the nostrils are sensitive to solutions of certain chemical substances. There are five basic taste sensations. The first four are sweet, sour, bitter and salt. Very recently scientists have discovered a fifth taste called umami. The receptors of taste and smell are essentially similar in function. In fact much of what is called taste is in fact a function of the sense of smell.', 'l3', 28),
('rp_u3_29', 'Your skin has three main layers. The lower layer, the hypodermis, contains fatty tissue which is both an energy store and acts as an insulation layer. The middle layer or dermis contains the blood vessels, the sweat glands, the sensory receptors and the hair follicles. The upper layer or epidermis is made up of dead cells. These stop water loss and also protect against the entry of pathogens.', 'l3', 29),
('rp_u3_30', 'Hormones act as chemical messages, produced in one part of the body but having an effect somewhere entirely different. Glands are structures which produce hormones and other useful substances. The endocrine glands that produce your hormones have no ducts. They secrete hormones directly into your blood.', 'l3', 30),
('rp_u3_31', 'The thyroid gland in your neck uses iodine from your diet to produce the hormone thyroxine. It controls the metabolic rate of your body. The most common reason for not making enough thyroxine is a lack of iodine in the diet. The gland will grow and enlarge in an attempt to make the right amount of thyroxine. This is known as goitre.', 'l3', 31),
('rp_u3_32', 'The pancreas is a small pink organ found below your stomach. It constantly monitors your blood glucose concentration and controls it using two hormones known as insulin and glucagon. Insulin stimulates your liver to remove any glucose which is not needed. Glucagon stimulates your liver to break down glycogen, converting it back into glucose.', 'l3', 32),
('rp_u3_33', 'For some people, their pancreas does not make enough – or any – insulin. Without insulin your blood sugar levels get higher and higher after you eat food. This is diabetes. Insulin injections treat diabetes successfully but they do not cure it.', 'l3', 33),
('rp_u3_34', 'Adrenaline is produced by your adrenal glands, which sit on top of your kidneys and it is the hormone of ‘fight or flight’. If you are stressed, angry, excited or frightened your adrenal glands will secrete lots of adrenalin. Adrenalin basically prepares your body for action.', 'l3', 34),
('rp_u3_35', 'The gonads are the endocrine glands which produce some of the sex hormones. These are the testes in boys and the ovaries in girls. The pituitary gland in your brain starts to produce increasing amounts of FSH. This stimulates the male gonads or testes to begin developing and producing the male sex hormone testosterone.', 'l3', 35),
('rp_u3_36', 'The female gonads are the ovaries. FSH from the brain stimulates the ovaries to become active and start producing the female sex hormone oestrogen. The menstrual cycle is a sequence of events which takes place approximately every four weeks throughout the fertile life of a woman. FSH stimulates the development of a follicle. LH stimulates the release of the egg. Oestrogen stimulates the lining of the uterus to build up. Progesterone maintains the thickened lining of the uterus.', 'l3', 36),
('rp_u3_37', 'For human reproduction to be successful the sperm made in the man’s testes must meet up and join with an ovum released from the woman’s ovary. The nucleus from the sperm, containing the chromosomes from the father, fuses with the nucleus from the ovum, containing chromosomes from the mother, and a potential new life begins. The new cell (known as the zygote) has a unique set of chromosomes.', 'l3', 37),
('rp_u3_38', 'Contraception means ‘against pregnancy’ and it describes ways in which pregnancy can be avoided. Natural methods are based on understanding the menstrual cycle and accurately predicting the moment of ovulation. Physical or barrier methods involve physical barriers like condoms or diaphragms which prevent the meeting of the ovum and the spermatozoa. Hormonal methods use variations on your natural hormones, like the pill or hormone injections, to prevent conception. Sterilisation or surgical contraception is the ultimate form of contraception. The IUD or intrauterine device interferes with and prevents the implantation of the early embryo.', 'l3', 38),
('rp_u3_39', 'Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) is the medical term for a combination of illnesses that result when the immune system is weakened or destroyed. It is the advanced form of an infection caused by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV). HIV can be spread through four bodily fluids – blood, semen, vaginal secretions and breast milk.', 'l3', 39),
('rp_u3_40', 'One of these harmful traditional practices is female genital mutilation (FGM). Female genital mutilation is a process which is carried out across Ethiopia. All of them involve removing part of the external genitalia of young girls in surgery which is carried out without any anaesthetic. The process of FGM when a girl is cut can result in serious bleeding and infections which can kill. In Ethiopia today, it can put our girls at risk of HIV infection too.', 'l3', 40),
('rp_u3_41', 'Homeostasis means keeping the conditions in the inside of your body (the internal environment) in the same state all the time. One of the most important factors which animals need to control is the internal or core body temperature. It is vitally important that wherever we go and whatever we do our body temperature is maintained at the temperature (around 37 °C) at which our enzymes work best.', 'l3', 41),
('rp_u3_42', 'Poikilotherms are organisms whose body temperature is governed by the external temperature. Homoiotherms are organisms with a relatively constant internal body temperature which is usually higher than the external temperature. Humans are a well-known example of homoiotherms.', 'l3', 42),
('rp_u3_43', 'Human body temperature is controlled by physiological mechanisms: Sweating, Vasodilation (blood vessels dilate to lose heat), Panting and licking, Vasoconstriction (blood vessels constrict to conserve heat), Piloerection (pulling the hairs upright), Shivering, and the fat layer under the skin. Control of the temperature relies on the thermoregulatory centre in the brain.', 'l3', 43),
('rp_u3_44', 'Excretion – getting rid of the waste products which could build up in your body and damage your cells – is one of the most important aspects of homeostasis. The main excretory organs in your body are your lungs, your kidneys and your skin. The carbon dioxide produced during cellular respiration is almost all removed from the body via the lungs when you breathe out. Urea is produced in your liver when excess amino acids are broken down. The urea is then filtered out of the blood by the kidneys and removed in the urine.', 'l3', 45),
('rp_u3_45', 'The balance of water and salts in your body is very important because of the osmotic impact on your cells if the balance is wrong so controlling this balance is known as osmoregulation. Bowman’s capsule is the site of the ultrafiltration of the blood. The amount of water lost from the kidney in the urine is controlled by a sensitive feedback mechanism involving the hormone ADH.', 'l3', 46),
('rp_u3_46', 'The liver also plays a large role in maintaining a constant internal environment. It plays a part in the control of sugar levels, balancing fats, protein metabolism (deamination), breakdown of worn-out red blood cells, formation of bile, control of toxins, and temperature control.', 'l3', 47);
INSERT INTO "Unit" (id, title, "BookId") VALUES ('u4', 'Unit 4: Plant Biology', 'b1');
INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, title, "unitId", index) VALUES ('l4', 'Photosynthesis and Transport', 'u4', 4);
INSERT INTO "RealParagraph" (id, content, "LessonId", "order") VALUES
('rp_u4_1', 'The leaf is flat and wide, giving a large surface area to collect light and short distances for gases to diffuse. The waxy cuticle is a waterproof layer to help prevent water loss. The palisade mesophyll is the main photosynthetic tissue of the plant. The lower epidermis has openings known as stomata which allow carbon dioxide to diffuse into the leaf and oxygen and water vapour to diffuse out. The vascular bundles contain the xylem and the phloem.', 'l4', 1),
('rp_u4_2', 'Plants produce their own food in a process known as photosynthesis. During photosynthesis light energy from the sun is absorbed by a green substance called chlorophyll that is found in the chloroplasts of some plant cells. The energy that is captured is used to convert carbon dioxide from the air and water from the soil into a simple sugar, glucose, with oxygen as a by-product.', 'l4', 2),
('rp_u4_3', 'Some of the glucose produced by photosynthesis is always converted into starch for storage, at least as a first step. This is because glucose is soluble and so could affect the water balance within the plant. Starch is insoluble, which means that it does not dissolve, so it has no effect on the concentration of solutions.', 'l4', 3),
('rp_u4_4', 'The light-dependent reactions cannot take place without light energy. The light energy is absorbed by chlorophyll molecules through activation of their electrons and used to split water molecules into hydrogen and oxygen. The hydrogen and ATP produced in the light reaction are then used in a series of reduction reactions that convert carbon dioxide into glucose. This stage of the process does not need light to take place and is known as the light-independent reaction.', 'l4', 4),
('rp_u4_5', 'A source of carbon is needed for the plants to synthesise sugars. Carbon dioxide from the air or in solution in water is the only form that plants can use in photosynthesis. Water is also needed, and water is the only source of hydrogen that plants can make use of. The final requirement for photosynthesis to take place is a way of capturing the energy from the sun and this is carried out by the green pigment chlorophyll.', 'l4', 5),
('rp_u4_6', 'Photosynthesis is one of the most important reactions on Earth. Around 35 x 10^15 kg of new biological material is produced every year as a result of photosynthesis. Almost all living organisms need oxygen for cellular respiration. That oxygen is produced as a waste product of photosynthesis.', 'l4', 6),
('rp_u4_7', 'Plants take up water through their roots. Water moves into the plant root cells across the cell membrane along a concentration gradient. The roots are covered with special cells, which have tiny hair-like extensions called the root hairs. These root hairs increase the surface area for osmosis to take place.', 'l4', 7),
('rp_u4_8', 'There are two separate transport systems in plants. The phloem is made up of living tissue and it is involved in the transport of organic materials – the nutrients made by photosynthesis – from the leaves to the rest of the plant. The xylem is the other transport tissue. It carries water and mineral ions from the soil around the plant. The xylem tissue is dead and there is no active transport taking place.', 'l4', 8),
('rp_u4_9', 'As water evaporates from the surface of the leaves, water is pulled up through the xylem to take its place. This constant moving of water molecules through the xylem from the roots to the leaves is what is known as the transpiration stream. As molecules evaporate away from the surface of the leaf, the following molecules are pulled upwards by cohesive forces between the water molecules.', 'l4', 9),
('rp_u4_10', 'In most flowering plants, growth starts when the seed begins to germinate. An embryo plant is made up of three main parts – the plumule (embryonic shoot), the radicle (embryonic root) and the cotyledons (embryonic leaves). The type of germination where the cotyledons are carried above the soil is called epigeal germination. Germination in which the cotyledons remain underground is called hypogeal germination.', 'l4', 10),
('rp_u4_11', 'Growth in plants is influenced by chemical messengers called plant hormones. Auxin (IAA) is the best-known plant hormone and it is involved in general plant growth. It stimulates the elongation of the new plant cells. The best-known function of auxins is in the responses of plants to the world around them. The responses of plants towards things such as light and gravity are called tropisms.', 'l4', 11),
('rp_u4_12', 'Movement in response to the stimulus of gravity is called geotropism. Roots are positively geotropic (they grow towards gravity) while shoots are negatively geotropic (they grow away from gravity). The type of response by which roots grow towards water is termed hydrotropism.', 'l4', 12);
INSERT INTO "Unit" (id, title, "BookId") VALUES ('u5', 'Unit 5: Conservation', 'b1');
INSERT INTO "Lesson" (id, title, "unitId", index) VALUES ('l5', 'Ecology and Environment', 'u5', 5);
INSERT INTO "RealParagraph" (id, content, "LessonId", "order") VALUES
('rp_u5_1', 'Natural resources include anything that is found naturally in the country which is useful to human beings. Natural resources can be classified as either renewable or non-renewable. Renewable resources are mainly living things and their products. Managed carefully, they can be used, reused and replaced. Non-renewable resources are not living, and when they are used they cannot be replaced.', 'l5', 1),
('rp_u5_2', 'Conservation is the protection and preservation of our natural environment, so that non-renewable resources are used sparingly and renewable resources are managed so that they can last for the foreseeable future.', 'l5', 2),
('rp_u5_3', 'Biodiversity is a measure of the wealth of species in a given place. Healthy biodiversity is important for the health of the planet. The air and water of the Earth are purified by a wide range of organisms. Biodiversity also gives us the genetic diversity we need to develop crops to grow in different conditions.', 'l5', 3),
('rp_u5_4', 'Ethiopia is a country which is internationally recognised for its rich diversity of plant species. We have around 7000 different species of higher plants alone, with up to 800 endemic species. An endemic species is an organism that is only found in a particular area.', 'l5', 4),
('rp_u5_5', 'The wildlife of Ethiopia is some of the richest in the world. We have 242 listed mammalian species, which range from huge elephants to tiny elephant shrews. There are around 862 species of birds as well. We have a high number of endemic species of different types of wildlife.', 'l5', 5),
('rp_u5_6', 'Pollution is the contamination of the natural environment by harmful substances as a result of human activities. One type of air pollution is smoke produced by burning fuel for energy. Another major cause of air pollution is the production of carbon dioxide. Carbon dioxide in the atmosphere is important because of the greenhouse effect. It traps some of the heat from the sun and keeps the surface of the Earth warm enough for life as we know it.', 'l5', 6),
('rp_u5_7', 'Sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxides pollute the air and can cause serious breathing problems for people. They form a haze of pollution known as smog. They are also involved in the formation of acid rain. The sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxides dissolve in the rain and react with oxygen in the air to form dilute sulphuric acid and nitric acid.', 'l5', 7),
('rp_u5_8', 'Another form of air pollution has led to the depletion of the ozone layer in the atmosphere. Ozone is a gas which is found in the atmosphere of the Earth. It absorbs some of the ultraviolet radiation from the sun. Air pollution by CFCs had caused the ozone layer around the Earth to get thinner.', 'l5', 8);